'''Waller Hall''' is the oldest building on the campus of [[Willamette University]] in [[Salem, Oregon]], [[United States]]. Built in 1867, Waller Hall was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in [[1975]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Oregon National Register List | publisher = Oregon Parks & Recreation Dept.: Heritage Programs: National Register | url= http://www.oregon.gov/OPRD/HCD/NATREG/docs/oregon_nr_list.pdf | format = [[PDF]] }}</ref>

==Construction==
[[Image:WallerHall.jpg|thumb|left|Early drawing of Waller Hall]]
The building was constructed beginning in 1864 on the north section of Willamette’s campus in downtown Salem.<ref name=eesi>[http://www.eesinet.com/WillametteUniv.pdf EESI]</ref> It was through the efforts of the Reverend Alvan F. Waller that the hall was built.<ref name=SOH>{{cite web| last = Gibby| first = Susan| title = Willamette University| publisher = Salem Online History| url = http://www.salemhistory.net/education/willamette_university.htm| accessdate =  2007-03-12}}</ref> All of the [[brick]]s used in the construction were fired on campus using clay dug up to build the foundation.<ref name=SOH/> The builders ordered 500,000 bricks for the project.<ref name=Walton>{{cite journal
  | last = Walton
  | first = Elisabeth
  | authorlink =
  | coauthors =
  | title = A Note on William W. Piper and Academy Architecture in Oregon in the Nineteenth Century
  | journal = The Journal of the Society of Architectural Historians
  | volume = 32
  | issue = 3
  | pages = 231-238
  | publisher =
  | date = Oct. 1973
  | url =
  | doi = 10.2307/988795
  | id =
  | accessdate = 2007-03-11 }}</ref> Construction was completed in 1867 and the building was named University Hall.<ref name=WU>[http://www.willamette.edu/tour/tour_flash.php Willamette University: Campus Tour]</ref> The President of the Board of Trustees, [[David Leslie (Oregon politician)|David Leslie]], laid the cornerstone of the hall.<ref name=salem>[http://www.open.org/~pioneerc/pg26.html#LeslDavi132 Salem Pioneer Cemetery]</ref> The building was first used for classrooms, a library, parlors, recitation rooms, and some physical education in the attic.<ref name=Walton/> In [[1912]] Willamette renamed the building in honor of Waller.<ref name=SOH/> In the early years the structure housed the chapel services of the school.<ref name=WU/>

==Architecture==
[[Image:BrickDentils.JPG|left|thumb|100px|Brick dentils]]
This red brick building was designed in the same proportions as a [[Greek cross]].<ref name=WU/> The hall has a [[cupola]] topping the structure. Each wing is 84 feet long and 44 feet wide with [[aedicule]] porches on the west, east, and north ends of the building.<ref name=Walton/> Other details included [[pilaster]]s, [[dentil]]s, and brick [[Corbel|corbelling]] on the exterior and a circular stairway on the interior.<ref name=Walton/>

==Fires==
In [[1891]] Waller Hall burned for the first time.<ref name=WU/> This time the top two floors of the building were destroyed.<ref name=WU/> Then in [[1919]] the five-story building was completely gutted by a second fire.<ref name=WU/> However, the university rebuilt the interior the following year.<ref name=SOH/>

==Currently==
After renovations completed in 1989, the building is still in use by the university.<ref name=WU/> Waller Hall houses alumni relations, the school’s business office, human resources for the university, the office of communications, university relations, the President’s office, and other administrative functions.<ref name=WU/> Additionally, the Cone Chapel is on the building's second floor and seats 300.<ref name=WU/> The chapel is occasionally used for commencement ceremonies for the school.<ref>[http://blog.willamette.edu/news/archives/2001/04/willamette_to_g.php WU: News]</ref> Waller Hall sits in the north central part of campus directly opposite of the [[Oregon State Capitol]]. Waller Hall is the oldest university building west of the [[Mississippi River]] still in use.<ref name=eesi/>

In 1992, during the university's [[anniversary|sesquicentennial]], the [[United States Postal Service]] issued a [[post card|postal card]] that featured an image of Waller Hall.<ref name=SOH/> 

